replies.bodyText:
This was already the case before but if was not clearly stated:
In TokenWarpScriptExtension.java when there was no secret in the conf nor OSS, the keystore was null:
if (null == TOKEN_SECRET) { // if no configuration key and if (null != ossHandledSecret) {...} else { keystore = null; }.
When the keystore was null, the TokenWarpScriptExtension constructor added the TOKENGEN and TOKENDUMP without keystore. It resulted in both keys to be null and multikey to be left to false. Then in TOKENDUMP we had
if ((null == AESKey || null == SipHashKey) && !this.multikey) {
      throw new WarpScriptException(getName() + " cannot be used in this context.");	
}

which resulted in an difficult-to-debug error message which in fact required the secret to be set.

